    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-02-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-02-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="474"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d474">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/704</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The French Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_JJAAJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jusserand</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 6, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 8.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: My Government informs me that
                    the German Federal Council, by order dated the 25th ultimo, decreed the seizure
                    by the German authorities of all the flour and cereals then in the Empire or
                    which might reach it on and after the first of this month.</p>
                <p>In compliance with instructions received I have the honor to call to your
                    excellency’s attention one of the effects necessarily produced by that decree
                    which is to make that class of merchandise, listed as conditional contraband,
                    liable to capture whoever may be the consignee named in the bill of lading. For
                    their mere arrival in Germany places them, by virtue of the aforesaid decree, at
                    the disposal of the enemy.</p>
                <p>Be pleased to accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JJAAJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jusserand</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
